{"run_id": "f66d929a-34d2-4e3b-92f1-e22c7d54ca6a", "provider": "claude_code", "model": "claude-opus-4-6", "prompt_version": "audit_v1", "target_file": "upnpredirect.c", "repo_revision": "cd506a67e174a45c6a202eff182a712955ed6d6f", "container_image": "minimythos:0.1", "harness_flags": [], "file_score": 5, "status": "candidate", "input_tokens": 15, "output_tokens": 11363, "cost_usd": 0.6958305, "cumulative_cost_usd": 12.54609325, "duration_seconds": 254.5, "tool_call_count": 0, "transcript_path": "/home/pyl/minimythos/runs/transcripts/f66d929a-34d2-4e3b-92f1-e22c7d54ca6a.jsonl", "retry_number": 0, "validation_verdict": null, "asan_triggered": null, "defect_report": "**Stack buffer overflow in `upnp_get_redirection_infos_by_index()` when protocol is UDPLITE**\n\n**Location:** `upnpredirect.c`, lines 539-540\n\n**What:** When `get_redirect_rule_by_index()` returns a rule with `proto == IPPROTO_UDPLITE`, the function executes `memcpy(protocol, \"UDPLITE\", 8)`, writing 8 bytes (7 characters + null terminator) into the caller-provided `protocol` buffer. However, the primary caller `upnp_get_portmapping_number_of_entries()` (line 585) declares `char protocol[4]`, which can only hold 4 bytes. This results in a 4-byte stack buffer overflow.\n\n**Root cause:** The `protocol` buffer was sized for `\"TCP\"` or `\"UDP\"` (4 bytes including null), but the `IPPROTO_UDPLITE` code path (added later, guarded by `#ifdef IPPROTO_UDPLITE`) writes `\"UDPLITE\"` which requires 8 bytes. The buffer size was never updated to accommodate this longer string.\n\n**Impact:** Stack buffer overflow that corrupts adjacent stack variables (`iaddr[32]` follows `protocol[4]` in the stack frame). Could potentially be exploited for code execution if an attacker can cause a UDPLITE port mapping rule to exist (e.g., via PCP or NAT-PMP protocol messages that support UDPLITE).\n\n**Trigger condition:** Any UDPLITE redirect rule in the netfilter tables when `upnp_get_portmapping_number_of_entries()` is called (which happens during normal UPnP operations like listing port mappings).\n\n**Confirmed by:** ASan output showing `WRITE of size 8` at the `protocol` variable (offset 84, size 4) in the stack frame of `upnp_get_portmapping_number_of_entries`, with the write originating from `memcpy` in `upnp_get_redirection_infos_by_index` at line 540.", "diagnostic_trigger": "#!/bin/bash\n# Trigger UDPLITE stack buffer overflow in upnp_get_redirection_infos_by_index()\n# Requires: ASan-instrumented build inside minimythos_run container\n\ndocker exec minimythos_run bash -c 'cd /opt/miniupnp/miniupnpd && cat > test_udplite_overflow.c << '\\''TESTEOF'\\''\n#include <stdlib.h>\n#include <string.h>\n#include <stdio.h>\n#include <sys/types.h>\n#include <sys/socket.h>\n#include <netinet/in.h>\n#include <net/if.h>\n#include <arpa/inet.h>\n#include <syslog.h>\n#include <time.h>\n\n#include \"config.h\"\n#include \"upnpredirect.h\"\n#include \"upnpglobalvars.h\"\n\n/* Stubs for all undefined symbols */\nconst char * ext_if_name = \"lo\";\nconst char * lease_file = NULL;\nint disable_port_forwarding = 0;\nunsigned int nextruletoclean_timestamp = 0;\nstruct upnpperm * upnppermlist = NULL;\nunsigned int num_upnpperm = 0;\n\nint check_upnp_rule_against_permissions(const struct upnpperm *p, int n,\n    unsigned short eport, struct in_addr addr, unsigned short iport) {\n    (void)p; (void)n; (void)eport; (void)addr; (void)iport;\n    return 1;\n}\n\n/* Mock: returns one UDPLITE rule at index 0, -1 for index > 0 */\nint get_redirect_rule_by_index(int index, char *ifname,\n    unsigned short *eport, char *iaddr, int iaddrlen,\n    unsigned short *iport, int *proto, char *desc, int desclen,\n    char *rhost, int rhostlen, unsigned int *timestamp,\n    u_int64_t *packets, u_int64_t *bytes) {\n    (void)ifname;\n    if (index > 0) return -1;\n    if (eport) *eport = 5000;\n    if (iaddr && iaddrlen > 0) snprintf(iaddr, iaddrlen, \"192.168.1.1\");\n    if (iport) *iport = 5000;\n    if (proto) *proto = IPPROTO_UDPLITE;\n    if (desc && desclen > 0) snprintf(desc, desclen, \"test\");\n    if (rhost && rhostlen > 0) rhost[0] = 0;\n    if (timestamp) *timestamp = 0;\n    if (packets) *packets = 0;\n    if (bytes) *bytes = 0;\n    return 0;\n}\n\nint get_redirect_rule(const char *ifname, unsigned short eport, int proto,\n    char *iaddr, int iaddrlen, unsigned short *iport,\n    char *desc, int desclen, char *rhost, int rhostlen,\n    unsigned int *timestamp, u_int64_t *packets, u_int64_t *bytes) {\n    (void)ifname; (void)eport; (void)proto; (void)iaddr; (void)iaddrlen;\n    (void)iport; (void)desc; (void)desclen; (void)rhost; (void)rhostlen;\n    (void)timestamp; (void)packets; (void)bytes;\n    return -1;\n}\n\nint add_redirect_rule2(const char *a, const char *b, unsigned short c,\n    const char *d, unsigned short e, int f, const char *g, unsigned int h) {\n    (void)a;(void)b;(void)c;(void)d;(void)e;(void)f;(void)g;(void)h;\n    return 0;\n}\nint add_filter_rule2(const char *a, const char *b, const char *c,\n    unsigned short d, unsigned short e, int f, const char *g) {\n    (void)a;(void)b;(void)c;(void)d;(void)e;(void)f;(void)g;\n    return 0;\n}\nint delete_redirect_and_filter_rules(unsigned short a, int b) {\n    (void)a;(void)b;\n    return 0;\n}\nint update_portmapping(const char *a, unsigned short b, int c,\n    unsigned short d, const char *e, unsigned int f) {\n    (void)a;(void)b;(void)c;(void)d;(void)e;(void)f;\n    return 0;\n}\nint update_portmapping_desc_timestamp(const char *a, unsigned short b,\n    int c, const char *d, unsigned int e) {\n    (void)a;(void)b;(void)c;(void)d;(void)e;\n    return 0;\n}\nunsigned short * get_portmappings_in_range(unsigned short a, unsigned short b,\n    int c, unsigned int *d) {\n    (void)a;(void)b;(void)c;(void)d;\n    return NULL;\n}\nvoid upnp_event_var_change_notify(int a) { (void)a; }\ntime_t upnp_time(void) { return time(NULL); }\n\nint main(void) {\n    fprintf(stderr, \"Calling upnp_get_portmapping_number_of_entries()...\\n\");\n    int n = upnp_get_portmapping_number_of_entries();\n    fprintf(stderr, \"Number of entries: %d\\n\", n);\n    return 0;\n}\nTESTEOF\ngcc -fsanitize=address,undefined -g -O0 -I. -o test_udplite_overflow test_udplite_overflow.c upnpredirect.c && ./test_udplite_overflow'", "no_finding_reason": null, "error_message": null, "raw_stderr": "", "timestamp": "2026-04-13T06:01:47.052657+00:00"}
{"run_id": "f66d929a-34d2-4e3b-92f1-e22c7d54ca6a", "event": "gate_b", "judge_verdict": "CONFIRMED", "judge_reasoning": "**ASan output confirms the overflow.** Running the trigger produced:\n\n```\nWRITE of size 8 at address 0x7b813e200054 thread T0\n    #0 in memcpy\n    #1 in upnp_get_redirection_infos_by_index upnpredirect.c:540\n    #2 in upnp_get_portmapping_number_of_entries upnpredirect.c:589\n\nAddress is located in stack of thread T0 at offset 84 in frame:\n    #0 upnp_get_portmapping_number_of_entries upnpredirect.c:582\n  [80, 84) 'protocol' (line 585) <== Memory access at offset 84 overflows this variable\n  [96, 128) 'iaddr' (line 585)\n```\n\nThe buffer `char protocol[4]` at line 585 receives an 8-byte write from `memcpy(protocol, \"UDPLITE\", 8)` at line 540, confirmed at the exact stack offsets reported.\n\n**SL-1 check \u2014 trigger is NOT synthetic.** The trigger mocks `get_redirect_rule_by_index` returning `IPPROTO_UDPLITE`. I verified this accurately represents the real netfilter backend (`netfilter/iptcrdr.c:439`): `*proto = e->ip.proto` reads the protocol number directly from the iptables entry with no translation. Any UDPLITE rule stored by `add_redirect_rule2()` would be returned as `IPPROTO_UDPLITE` verbatim. The mock faithfully simulates this \u2014 it is only needed because running real iptables requires privileges the test environment lacks.\n\n**SL-2 check \u2014 not UB-only.** This is a concrete, in-bounds-to-out-of-bounds write of 8 bytes into a 4-byte stack buffer. It corrupts the adjacent `iaddr[32]` variable (at stack offset 96). No compiler optimization is needed to observe the wrong behavior; the stack corruption is real on all platforms.\n\n**Real network attack path:**\n\n1. **Attacker sends UPnP AddPortMapping SOAP request** with `NewProtocol=UDPLITE`. Confirmed in `upnpsoap.c:517`: the handler calls `upnp_redirect(..., protocol, ...)` with the raw protocol string \u2014 there is no protocol validation that blocks UDPLITE for port mappings (the UDPLITE check at line 1685-1693 is in the `AddPinhole` IPv6 handler, not `AddPortMapping`).\n\n2. **`proto_atoi(\"UDPLITE\")`** in `upnpredirect.c:63-", "retry_handoff": null, "focus_file": "upnpredirect.c", "cost_usd": 0.41081445, "input_tokens": 18, "output_tokens": 9863, "duration_seconds": 178.4, "judge_transcript_path": "/home/pyl/minimythos/runs/judge_transcripts/judge_f66d929a-34d2-4e3b-92f1-e22c7d54ca6a.jsonl", "timestamp": "2026-04-13T06:04:45.447768+00:00"}
